"Internal promotions for senior engineering roles appear to require stronger executive relationships and multiple levels of personal advocacy than external hires, which can be decided more directly by the hiring manager. This creates a perception that advancement depends more on visibility and personal connections than on demonstrated impact, results, and technical contributions. To better reward high performers and retain top talent, consider:
Reducing the number of executive approvals required for strong internal candidates (align closer to external hiring autonomy).
Making promotion criteria fully transparent and quantifiable (e.g., clear rubrics tied to measurable outcomes like project delivery, innovation, mentorship, etc.).
Implementing structured, multi-source performance calibration that prioritizes evidence of results over subjective endorsements.
These changes would make internal mobility feel more merit-driven and equitable."
